06141nam a22007215i 9780824856175DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222016hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248561757 a10.1515/97808248561752doi  a(DE-B1597)612189  a(OCoLC)1322124826  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aHQ1032b.K386 2016 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a306.822231 aKawakami, Barbara F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPicture Bride Stories /cBarbara F. Kawakami. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2022] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b86 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: The Early Immigration Period to Hawaii -- tThe Brides -- tStolen Kaki and the Motorbike Santa -- tIssei Pioneers Who Paved the Way -- tTragedy and Triumph -- tFrom Hiroshima to the Pupukea Pineapple Fields -- tStrong and Resilient Like the Bamboo -- tSongs of Endurance and Perseverance -- tThe Scent of Golden Pineapples -- tGambare Spirit (Never Give Up) -- tFrom Washington Place to the Royal Hawaiian Hotel -- tThe Spirit of Sho-Chiku-Bai -- tInspiration from Tattered Clothing -- t“Two Pictures Got Married to Each Other” -- tThe Unsuspecting Picture Bride -- tShouldering Hundred-Pound Bags of Pula Pula -- tGomen Yo (Forgive Me), It Was the Sake -- tIn Search of a Father’s Beckoning Spirit -- tEpilogue -- tDr. Tomizo Katsunuma -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the 1885 to 1924 immigration period of plantation laborers from Japan to Hawaii, more than 200,000 Japanese, mostly single men, made the long journey by ship to the Hawaiian Islands. As it became apparent that they would never return to Japan, many of the men sent for brides to join them in their adopted home. More than 20,000 of these “picture brides” immigrated from Japan and Okinawa to Hawaii to marry husbands whom they knew only through photographs exchanged between them or their families.Based on Barbara F. Kawakami’s first-hand interviews with sixteen of these women, Picture Bride Stories is a poignant collection that recounts the diverse circumstances that led them to marry strangers, their voyages to Hawaii, the surprises and trials that they encountered upon arriving, and the lives they led upon settling in a strange new land. Many found hardship, yet persevered and endured the difficult conditions of the sugarcane and pineapple plantations for the sake of their children. As they acclimated to a foreign place and forged new relationships, they overcame challenges and eventually prospered in a better life. The stories of the issei women exemplify the importance of friendships and familial networks in coping with poverty and economic security. Although these remarkable women are gone, their legacy lives on in their children, grandchildren, and succeeding generations.In addition to the oral histories—the result of forty years of interviews—the author provides substantial background on marriage customs and labor practices on the plantations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMail order brides - Hawaii. 0aMail order brideszHawaiivBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh1 aAsato, Kama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFujimoto, Kikuyo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiga, Kana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaigo, Shizu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKawakami, Hisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aK